      <hedline>
        <hl1>Bush's Texas Record Raises a Question</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Howard Manas letter on excuse that Gov George W Bush is not to blame for Texas's social problems; asks what, besides his name, then qualifies Bush for Presidency if he has accomplished so little in Texas (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''What a Texas Record Can't Tell'' (Op-Ed, April 28): Paul Burka is trying to get across the point that Gov. George W. Bush should not and cannot be blamed for most of the social problems and deficiencies that Texas has because that conservative state has long-held restraints on what its governors can accomplish politically.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''What a Texas Record Can't Tell'' (Op-Ed, April 28): Paul Burka is trying to get across the point that Gov. George W. Bush should not and cannot be blamed for most of the social problems and deficiencies that Texas has because that conservative state has long-held restraints on what its governors can accomplish politically.</p>
        <p>My question is, if Governor Bush has accomplished little as Texas's chief executive, how is he qualified to serve as president of the United States? Basically, he is running without any track record. Perhaps if his name weren't Bush, he would just be one of the also-rans who took part in this year's Republican primaries.</p>
        <p>HOWARD MANAS  Parlin, N.J., April 28, 2000</p>
      </block>
